Classification Question

Math 440

The data and question

  1. Load the iris data set that comes with your R installation, and give it the name df:
df <- iris

This data set has 4 measurements (petal length and width, and sepal length and width) associated with three different species of iris: setosa, versicolor, virginica

Goal: Build a general linear model to predict the species from given measurements of the flower. To do such a thing, we first add a column to our data frame that encodes the species as a numeric variable.

df$code=ifelse(df$Species=="setosa",0,ifelse(df$Species=="versicolor",1,2))
  1. Separate the data into training and testing data. We randomly select 80% of the observations to be placed in the train data set. We build our model on these observations. We then test our model on the remaining 20% of the data, the test data.
p=.8 # proportion of data going into the training group
n=nrow(df) # total number of observations in the data set
train.rows<-sample.int(n,n*p,replace=FALSE)
train <- df[train.rows,]
test <- df[-train.rows,]

Example

  1. Take a look at the training data. Does knowing Sepal length and width allow us to predict the species?
ggplot(train)+
  geom_point(aes(x=Sepal.Length,y=Sepal.Width,col=Species))

  1. Build a general linear model for predicting species from Sepal length and width.

We build the linear model by using the variable code that we created to encode the species with a numeric variable.

  • 0 = setosa
  • 1 = versicolor
  • 2 = virginica
model <- lm(code~Sepal.Length+Sepal.Width,train)
  1. Use the model to make predictions for each observation in the testing data
predictions<-round(predict(model,newdata=test)) 
# the round() command rounds the predicted code value to a whole number
  1. Display predictions and actual species type:
results <- data.frame(actual=test$code,predicted=predictions)
results %>%
  kable(caption="Testing Data") %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"),full_width=FALSE,position="left")

  1. How well did our model predict species?
sum(predictions==test$code)
## [1] 23

So, we correctly classified 23 of the 30 observations in the test data. Not surprisingly, our model is good at identifying setosa (0), and not as good at distinguishing between versicolor and virginica.
